Forecasting with Boosted Decision Trees and Threshold Autoregressive Models

I-Lun, Tu

1. Boosted Decision Trees with LightGBM

(1) Introduction

We framed the problem of deciding whether or not to buy certain ETFs before the market closed as classification problems in the statistical learning/ machine learning context. That is, if the following day’s opening price was higher than today’s close price (positive return), our model should provide us with a signal. On the other hand, for a negative return, our model should indicate a sell signal. We modeled each of the 6 ETFs separately. However, we used the same statistical learning framework but with different parameters to optimize the results.

(2) Methodology

a. Statistical Learning Models

The Boosted decision tree with LightGBM framework was utilized for handling the classification tasks. LightGBM was known for its accuracy in prediction and efficiency in execution. LightGBM was on par, if not slightly better, than the XGBoost framework, with which many teams won the Kaggle data competitions several years ago. Also, in the current literature on short-term stock movement prediction, boosted decision tree was consistently one of the top-performing models.

b. Predictor Variables/ Features

Technical indicators were important factors for the movement of stock prices, as they actively affected many investors’ decisions and provided general information for stocks. With some experimentations, 10 technical indicators, including trend, momentum, and volatility indicators, were selected. In addition, since the ETFs in consideration were composed mainly of stocks in the technology sector, the Nasdaq index was used to provide another set of 10 technical indicators. Therefore, in total, there were 24 variables for the models to learn from, in addition to the original Open, High, Low, Close, and Volume data. (Open data was removed after the calculation of technical indicators to avoid data redundancy)

(3) Backtesting Frameworks

a. Backtesting Frameworks

The data started from 2018-01-01 to 2022-05-31. The idea was that we should not use data too long ago, or we would risk making obsolete models. Also, due to the time-series nature of the data, we trained, validated, and tested models using the below three different frameworks. The first one was the most straightforward testing framework. The second one intended to keep the models as up-to-date as possible. The third one was designed to make the models use as much information as possible.

b. Simple Training-Validation-Testing Splits

  • Testing Data (2022-01-01 ~ 2022-05-31/ 103 trading days): this set of data was reserved as out-of-sample data for the final testing. The final model would not have any knowledge of the data to guarantee the legitimacy of the testing results. Once the model was tuned and selected, we predicted the testing data using the same set of training data.

  • Training Data (2018-01-01 ~ 2021-05-27/ 857 trading days): this set of data was 85% percent of the remaining data and was used as the training data for models with different combinations of parameters to learn. There were in total 75 different combinations to choose from.

  • Validation Data (2021-05-28 ~ 2021-12-31/ 151 trading days): this set of data was 15% of the remaining data and was used to compare and validate the training results. That is, we selected the highest-performing model based on this data set for the final testing.

c. Rolling-based Training-Validation-Testing Splits with a fixed window

  • Testing Data (2022-01-01 ~ 2022-05-31/ 103 trading days): the same setting as the previous framework. However, once the model was selected, we only predicted for the next day (1-day ahead prediction) with a fixed amount of training points. We slid the input data forward for a day every day starting from 2022-01-01. That is, we used 857 data points immediately before 2022-01-01 to predict 2022-01-01. Next, we used 857 days of data points immediately before 2022-01-02 (trimmed out the most distant date) to predict 2022-01-02.

  • Training Data (2018-01-01 ~ 2021-05-27/ 857 trading days): the same setting as the previous framework. However, the training process was similar to testing in the sense that we also slid forward the training data each time by 1 day.

  • Validation Data (2021-05-28 ~ 2021-12-31/ 151 trading days): the same setting as the previous framework. We validated the quality of prediction 1-day each time in the same vein as how we tested the model in this framework.

d. Rolling-based Training-Validation-Testing Splits with an enlarging window

  • Testing Data (2022-01-01 ~ 2022-05-31/ 103 trading days): the same setting as the previous framework. However, we made the input data larger each time by a day. That is, first we used all the data except testing data (2018-01-01 ~ 2021-12-31) to form the 1-day ahead prediction. For the second prediction, we incorporated the previously predicted first day to make use of the new data point.

  • Training Data (2018-01-01 ~ 2021-05-27/ 857 trading days): the same setting as the previous framework. However, the training process was similar to testing in the sense that the training data also became larger each time by 1 day.

  • Validation Data (2021-05-28 ~ 2021-12-31/ 151 trading days): the same setting as the previous framework. We validated the quality of prediction 1-day each in the same vein of how we tested the model in this framework.

e. Model Testing Results

  • Positive Percentage: among all the days in the testing data, what proportion of days came with a positive return.

  • Validation Accuracy: the highest accuracy achieved when adjusting/ tuning the models using validation data.

  • Testing Accuracy: the accuracy when the models were tested on the never-before-seen data. The larger the discrepancy between testing accuracy and validation accuracy, the stronger the indication that the underlying market was harder to predict for this model.

  • True Positive: among those days with positive returns, what proportion was correctly identified by the model.

  • True Negative: among those days with negative returns, what proportion was correctly identified by the model. (Low True Negative suggested a higher rate of false-positive)

  • Long Signal: the number of times the models predicted that we should buy.

  • Long: the resulting profit if we only placed long position entirely according to the models.

  • Short Signal: the number of times the models predicted that we should sell/ not buy.

  • Short: the resulting profit if we only placed short position entirely according to the models.

  • Long Short: the resulting profit if we place both long and short positions entirely according to the models.

(5) Interpretation & Suggestion

For a good model, we should expect that it had noticeably higher accuracy than 50% both in validation and testing accuracy. We should also expect the model to have good performance on both true positive and true negative rate, because sometimes if the underlying market was bullish, we would observe a higher than 50% true positive rate even if the model did not have a good predictive ability. In addition, to be robust and consistent, the model should perform well on all three types of backtesting frameworks. With these criteria in mind, we would suggest that we had not yet find a definitive model. On a positive note, the model for IEMG in the first backtesting framework and the model for AAXJ in the third backtesting framework (Table 2 & Table 6) seemed to have some earning potentials.
 

Regarding profits, the results suggest that it was a bit more profitable to place short positions. This may have something to do with the fact that the market was in bearish condition and the disproportionate positive and negative returns. For example, in the IEMG simple backtesting framework, the model was able to identify positive and negative return with relatively equal success, yet there was a large difference in the resulting profit.

(6) Possible Improvement & Further Research Direction

The set of technical indicators utilized in this study was suggested by previous researches and were composed of many commonly used indicators. With some experimentations, we discovered that this set indeed help the model achieve higher accuracy. However, as we understood there were many more potentially useful indicators, and more importantly, there were exponentially more combinations of these indicators.
 

Moving forward, we would like to use genetic algorithm to systemically explore the vast number of possible combinations. Also, to make more use of the time-series structure of the data, we would also like to experiment with the SPADE algorithm to extract other possible trading signals. Our goal was to uniformly increase the overall accuracy in the previously mentioned metrics to around 55%.

2. Dynamic Time Series Models - Threshold AutoRegressive Models

(1) Introduction

The primary reasons behind the under-performing boosted decision tree models might be that they were not “dynamic” enough in the sense that they had to balance many data points in the past. Often, short-term movements were more heavily influenced by certain recent factors, and even with similar information from our selected covariates, we would not have a better chance of predicting the correct movements, if the underlying market conditions were different.

Therefore, we turned to use the more straightforward and more compatible time series models. We selected the Threshold AutoRegressive models. The idea was that we not only wanted to model the price movement from fewer past instances, but more importantly, we intended to capture how the market would react or how the market conditions would change when the price reached certain levels/ thresholds. We experimented with different thresholds and discovered the quality of predictions was reasonably well (around 62% directional accuracy for some of our targets).

(2) Training and Validation Process

For time series models, a more traditional AIC/ BIC criterion selection methods were used. That is, the data set was splited between training and testing. After training on the training data set, the selected time series model was used to predict out-of-sample testing data set to calculate the directional accuracy and the resulting profit.

(3) Profit Calculation

Based on the below testings starting from 2022-01-01, we could see that there seemed to be some earning potential for EEMA and AAXJ for both the long and short positions. Hence, we suggested focusing more on these ETFs. Overall speaking, assuming short positions tended to generate more profits compared with assuming long positions, although, of course, it was more risky and costly to assume the short position. (Notice there were cut-off value set at the medium of the negative prediction to safeguard against short selling)

3. Conclusion and Future Development

The time series models performed quite well. However, its performance drop during period of interest rate hike. We could relax the cut-off value a bit to retain more of the competitive edge from short selling, and closely monitor the trading results to wait for the accuracy to come back to 60% to resume action. Yet, the above two methods are only superficial. To address the issue, we should add other methods to predict the timing and magnitude of reaction for upcoming events in general. For example, models for months that have interest rate hike. During the particular event period, we extend our trading windows and limit the next-day trading to benefit from longer term trend and to guard against volatile short term market. That is, event driven predictive models or short term swing trading methods. Combining the advantage of regime switching models and event driven models, the predictive model as a whole could be more robust and capture more gains from tough market conditions.
